Chapter 1
Cohren
0430 Itania-Time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He especially hated it because he was responsible for waking up all the others in his squad. He stood silently from his bunk, put on his combat gear, threw his body armor over, and retrieved his belongings from the locker, being careful with a certain small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Attached to it was everything he needed, like his breathing apparatus or his special goggles. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks. Outside, the mud and ice crunched under his boots.
He took a lighter from one jacket pocket and a cigarette from the other. He lit it and took a short puff before slightly opening the door. In the last week, he had to come up with quite a few tricks to wake up the men and women under his command. He no longer used the pre-set wake-up alarm, because it usually didn't work and only produced a faint noise from the speakers.
“Wake them up?” Cohren turned around and saw Squad Leader Nemic approaching him.
„Yes“, answered Cohren.
„What are you going to try this time?“
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and a few others came up to him already in full gear.
„Good morning“, said Craith.
„From what did you wake up?“, asked Cohren.
„So, first of all, we didn't feel like waiting to see what you'd come up with today. And secondly, the shock troops, who are the first to get up, get to choose the morning ration," replied one of the men, Ravik. „And you know how bad the food can be."
„Good point, Corporal," said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a switch. A loud, shrill alarm rang out in the barracks. Inside, he heard quiet cursing and people running around in confusion.
„Come on, Valturi," said Nemic. „You'd think they'd have learned by now to wake up at the same time as you."
„Well, my men from the training camp have learned," replied Cohren, pointing at Harris, Craith, and Ravik. „However, the platoon and squad leaders also know that they have to get up before their units."
Seconds later, the rest of the company came out. They had everything they needed, from personal items to the necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, others more annoyed.
„Good morning“, said Cohren in a good mood.
„With all due respect, Sir, why are you waking us up so early?“, asked a staff sergeant from the shock troops.
„Because the regular alarms are crap and because Daybreak doesn't sleep“, said Cohren.
„Pack all your personal belongings“, continued Cohren. As a lieutenant colonel and executive officer of the company, he was responsible for overseeing and supporting them together with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. „We are not coming back here. Staff sergeants and lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for the final checks and to pack your daily rations.“
The members of the Exodus Company dispersed quickly. They were part of the second shock troop division, second army. Before they were merged, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was split, and that was the main reason why Cohren had mixed feelings about his promotion to lieutenant colonel.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first squad, walked side by side in the light of the many generator-powered lamps of the forward deployment base. Most of them had red-tinted glass to avoid being detected by enemy bombers. Daybreak had relied on Wild-Weasel attacks from the air and on the ground to combat them.
„A new day and a new task for the Hellhounds“, said Nemic with a dry laugh. „Where are they sending us?“
„A forward deployment base outside of Ianlos. We will support the ground attack“, answered Cohren and took a drag on his cigarette. He gave Craith partial blame for starting to smoke, but a year in the field changed a person, so he said nothing.
„Damn. Things are getting worse at the front“, muttered Nemic. „All the messages say: «Support the war efforts. Send help to the Kurgan front.» How about help for the Howland front?“
„Amen, brother“, said Cohren and flicked the remains of his cigarette into the mud. „At least we're starting with the first armed squad and don't have to run. Captain Shaw should already be here.“
„Shaw has arranged a ride for us?“, asked Nemic a little surprised.
„Yes. He's honestly not as bad as I thought. He's not particularly approachable, but you can put up with him.“
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone and did so while putting on his backpack. „All units of the Exodus Company will meet at the West Parking Lot once they're ready. We'll depart with the first armed squad at 0500.“
In the second-by-second rhythm, he received responses from the squad leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they all came here. The four had been close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren had the feeling he had known them forever, even though it had only been at most two years. They were squad leaders, although Craith had been leading the second squad for a week, after the previous leader had been relieved due to medical reasons, following an assassination attempt by a Daybreak sharpshooter.
On the way to the parking lot, Cohren and Nemic noticed a group of about eight Kronos battle tanks and four infantry tanks. Their crews were running around, making sure their machines were combat-ready. Quickly, Cohren spotted Major Boradin Shaw, who was speaking with the commander of the armed squad. As they approached, Shaw looked over at them and came towards them, as always with an expressionless face.
„Lieutenant Nemic… Lieutenant Valturi…“ He said, Cohren was slower, while he looked at Cohren's pistol holsters and then looked up again. „The company is ready, I assume?“
